                                                                <customfield id="customfield_17518" key="com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.customfieldtypes:textarea">
                        <customfieldname>Quality Checks</customfieldname>
                        <customfieldvalues>
                            <customfieldvalue>&lt;p&gt;Refer to: &lt;a href="https://theverygroup.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/ADDSLF/pages/4849467604/Ways+of+Working" class="external-link" rel="nofollow noreferrer"&gt;https://theverygroup.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/ADDSLF/pages/4849467604/Ways+of+Working&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ready for development:&lt;br/&gt;
To ensure a task is "Ready for Development," the following criteria should ideally be met. If a ticket does not meet all criteria, the decision to include it in the sprint must be documented, specifying unmet requirements. QA can push such tickets back until the criteria are satisfied or appropriate contingencies are in place.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Meets INVEST Principles:  Independent, Negotiable, Valuable, Estimable, Small, and Testable.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Clear and Agreed Acceptance Criteria (AC):  &lt;br/&gt;
Note: Tickets without full Gherkin ACs may proceed if requirements are clearly documented. QA should update ACs to Gherkin format during development or QA stages.&lt;br/&gt;
Structured and agreed upon by all stakeholders (QA and Tech Lead).  &lt;br/&gt;
Written in Gherkin format: Given, When, Then.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] User Story Format: Defined as: As a &lt;span class="error"&gt;&amp;#91;user&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;, I want to &lt;span class="error"&gt;&amp;#91;action&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;, so that &lt;span class="error"&gt;&amp;#91;outcome&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Designs Aligned with ACs:  &lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Figma designs must cover all ACs.&lt;br/&gt;
Missing designs (e.g., error states/skeletons) should be flagged in the design channel.  dslf-uxd-collab&lt;br/&gt;
Associated design tickets must be linked or referenced.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Complete Information for Development:  &lt;br/&gt;
Dependencies and constraints are identified and understood.  &lt;br/&gt;
Dependencies must have linked tickets.  &lt;br/&gt;
Open questions and answers are documented.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Test Approach Defined:  Agreed exploratory and automation test approaches are documented.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Technical Approach Defined:  Technical implementation details are included in the story.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] No Outstanding Issues Blocking Delivery:  Material questions or dependencies must be resolved or highlighted in the ticket.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Estimation and Prioritisation:  User story/task is estimated and prioritised by the squad.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Test Data Availability:  Required test data is identified, available, or requested.&lt;br/&gt;
Note: A mini kickoff between a developer and QA is recommended to finalise and document acceptance criteria in the ticket before development begins.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ready for QA checklist&lt;br/&gt;
To ensure that a ticket is ready for a QA to review the following needs to be checked, done&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] "Ready for development" Criteria Met:  Requirements for "Ready for development" are satisfied.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Code Review Completed:  Adheres to coding standards and reviewed by at least one other developer.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Updated Ticket Description:  Description includes details of the implemented logic, such as API endpoints.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Developer Testing done:  Developers performed testing (unit, integration, etc.)&lt;br/&gt;
Note: Code lacking adequate tests should fail code reviews immediately.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Integration Testing on Preprd1:  Happy path integration test in the preprd1 environment to verify endpoint connectivity&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] UX/Figma Design Review:  Another developer must review UX/Figma designs as part of the code review process.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Acceptance Criteria Fulfilment:  All acceptance criteria on the ticket must be met before passing it to QA.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Local Testing Before Merge:  &lt;br/&gt;
QA tests the ticket locally before merging to master.  &lt;br/&gt;
Exception: Initial merge requests (MRs) by developers for non-live features do not require this step.&lt;br/&gt;
If a ticket fails QA and is sent back, any further changes must be tested locally before another merge and deployment to the preprd1 environment.  &lt;br/&gt;
Ideally, developers and QA should pair up briefly to demo fixes, reducing delays and avoiding "ticket tennis."&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Unit Tests:  Unit tests are written and pass successfully.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] End-to-End (E2E) Tests:  E2E tests are added or updated as needed and pass successfully.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Mocks for Verification:  Necessary mocks are created and tested to verify acceptance criteria.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Fusion Integration Testing :  Tested with Fusion integration where possible.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Contract Tests: Contract tests are written and pass successfully.&lt;br/&gt;
If contract tests are a separate ticket, the ticket should be linked.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Feature or Fix Validation:  The feature or fix is tested locally, and all acceptance criteria are verified.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Documentation:  Relevant documentation is completed, or a backlog ticket is raised for it if applicable.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ready for UAT:&lt;br/&gt;
To ensure a ticket is "Ready for UAT," the following criteria must be met. These build upon the "Ready for QA" requirements and include additional steps specific to UAT preparation.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Ready for QA Checks done:  All “Ready for QA" checks done&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Deployed to Testing Environment:  The feature or fix is deployed to the appropriate testing environment.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] End-to-End Automation Testing:  Agreed E2E automation tests are completed and passing.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Exploratory Testing Completed:  Exploratory testing has been conducted, and results are satisfactory.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] No Outstanding Critical Defects:  No unresolved P1 (critical) or P2 (high-priority) defects remain against the story.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Defects Logged and Triaged:  Any defects identified during testing are logged as tickets and triaged appropriately.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Non-Functional Testing (NFT):  Non-functional testing is completed or implemented, including:  &lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Performance testing - Page level (Lighthouse)&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Security testing  &lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Accessibility testing  &lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Logging and monitoring  &lt;br/&gt;
[ ] NFT test reports are included in the ticket.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Demo Recording:  A demo of the feature or fix is recorded and attached to the ticket.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] Test Report Attached:  A test report is added to the ticket, summarising all relevant testing activities and results.&lt;br/&gt;
[ ] UAT Test Data Prepared:  Test data required for UAT is fully prepared and documented in the UAT information pages. &lt;/p&gt;</customfieldvalue>

                        </customfieldvalues>
                    </customfield>
